🧠 Introduction

File handling allows Python programs to store and retrieve data from files.

Instead of losing data when a program closes, files help save information permanently.

---

🔹 What is File Handling?

```text id="file_handling_def"
File handling is the process of creating, reading, writing, and modifying files using Python.
```

---

🎯 Why File Handling is Important

✔ Store data permanently
✔ Read existing data
✔ Generate reports
✔ Process large datasets
✔ Used in real-world applications

---

📂 Types of Files

| File Type | Example |
| ---------- | ---------- |
| Text File | `.txt` |
| CSV File | `.csv` |
| JSON File | `.json` |
| Excel File | `.xlsx` |
| Log File | `.log` |

---

🔓 Opening a File

Python uses the `open()` function.

---

🔹 Syntax

```python id="open_syntax"
file = open("filename.txt", "mode")
```

---

📌 Parameters

| Parameter | Meaning |
| ---------- | ---------- |
| filename | Name of file |
| mode | Operation type |

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📖 Reading Files

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 Read Entire File

```python id="read_file"
file = open("sample.txt", "r")

content = file.read()

print(content)

file.close()
```

---

🔹 Sample File Content

```text id="sample_content"
Hello Python
Welcome to File Handling
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="read_output"
Hello Python
Welcome to File Handling
```

---

📄 Read One Line

```python id="readline_example"
file = open("sample.txt", "r")

print(file.readline())

file.close()
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="readline_output"
Hello Python
```

---

📄 Read All Lines

```python id="readlines_example"
file = open("sample.txt", "r")

print(file.readlines())

file.close()
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="readlines_output"
['Hello Python\n', 'Welcome to File Handling']
```

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

✍️ Writing Files

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 Write Mode (`w`)

Creates a file if it doesn't exist.

If file exists, old content is removed.

---

💻 Example

```python id="write_example"
file = open("data.txt", "w")

file.write("Learning Python")

file.close()
```

---

📌 File Content

```text id="write_content"
Learning Python
```

---

➕ Append Mode (`a`)

Adds new data without removing existing content.

---

💻 Example

```python id="append_example"
file = open("data.txt", "a")

file.write("\nFile Handling")

file.close()
```

---

📌 Updated File Content

```text id="append_content"
Learning Python
File Handling
```

---

🆕 Creating Files

Using write mode automatically creates files.

---

💻 Example

```python id="create_file"
file = open("newfile.txt", "w")

file.write("New File Created")

file.close()
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔒 Closing Files

Always close files after use.

---

💻 Example

```python id="close_example"
file = open("sample.txt", "r")

print(file.read())

file.close()
```

---

⚠️ Why Close Files?

✔ Free system resources
✔ Prevent data corruption
✔ Improve performance

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🛡️ Using with Statement

Recommended method for file handling.

Automatically closes files.

---

💻 Example

```python id="with_example"
with open("sample.txt", "r") as file:
    content = file.read()

print(content)
```

---

🎯 Benefits of with

✔ Cleaner code
✔ Automatic file closing
✔ Better exception handling

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📋 File Modes in Python

| Mode | Description |
| ------ | ------ |
| `r` | Read file |
| `w` | Write file |
| `a` | Append data |
| `x` | Create new file |
| `r+` | Read and write |
| `w+` | Write and read |
| `a+` | Append and read |
| `rb` | Read binary file |
| `wb` | Write binary file |

---

💻 Example: Read and Write

```python id="read_write_mode"
file = open("data.txt", "r+")

print(file.read())

file.write("\nPython")

file.close()
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

❌ Handling File Not Found Error

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Example

```python id="file_error"
try:
    file = open("unknown.txt", "r")

except FileNotFoundError:
    print("File not found")
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="file_error_output"
File not found
```

---

📊 Reading File Line by Line

---

💻 Example

```python id="line_by_line"
with open("sample.txt", "r") as file:

    for line in file:
        print(line.strip())
```

